+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0175YWBYR3rmfaMQFc5NRm8W","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\n\n# Plugin Marketplace -- Code Review Report\n\n## Executive Summary\n\n**Build**: PASSES  \n**Lint**: PASSES  \n**Tests**: 85/85 PASS across 6 test suites  \n\nThe implementation is well-structured, follows the required architecture, and conforms to all interfaces defined in `src/types.ts`. All five modules plus the integration layer are implemented. The code is clean, readable, and the test coverage is solid. Below is a detailed analysis with issues categorized by severity.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Plan Alignment Analysis\n\nAll six required components are implemented and accounted for:\n\n| Requirement | Status | Location |\n|---|---|---|\n| Plugin Registry (SQLite-backed) | Implemented | `/workspace/src/registry/index.ts` |\n| Version Resolver (semver) | Implemented | `/workspace/src/resolver/index.ts` |\n| Sandboxed Runner (vm) | Implemented | `/workspace/src/runner/index.ts` |\n| Review System | Implemented | `/workspace/src/reviews/index.ts` |\n| Dependency Graph | Implemented | `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts` |\n| Integration layer (createMarketplace + installPlugin) | Implemented | `/workspace/src/index.ts` |\n\nThe `installPlugin` workflow follows the exact prescribed sequence: validate -> register -> resolve deps -> check cycles -> execute in sandbox -> return result.\n\nThe constraint \"Modules should only share types, not import each other directly\" is respected. The only cross-module imports happen in `/workspace/src/index.ts` (the integration layer), which is the correct place for composition.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Interface Conformance\n\nAll service interfaces from `/workspace/src/types.ts` are implemented with matching signatures:\n\n- **RegistryService**: All 8 methods (`register`, `get`, `getVersion`, `list`, `search`, `remove`, `listVersions`, `update`) -- CONFORMS\n- **ResolverService**: All 4 methods (`resolve`, `satisfies`, `maxSatisfying`, `validRange`) -- CONFORMS\n- **RunnerService**: Both methods (`execute`, `executeWithTimeout`) -- CONFORMS\n- **ReviewService**: All 8 methods (`addReview`, `getReviews`, `getAverageRating`, `flagReview`, `getFlaggedReviews`, `removeReview`, `getReviewsByUser`, `getReviewCount`) -- CONFORMS\n- **DepsService**: All 5 methods (`buildTree`, `detectCycles`, `topologicalSort`, `flattenDependencies`, `hasCircularDependency`) -- CONFORMS\n\n---\n\n## 3. What Was Done Well\n\n**Clean module architecture.** Each service is a self-contained factory function with no cross-dependencies. The integration layer composes them properly.\n\n**Correct use of SQLite.** Both the registry and review service use `better-sqlite3` with WAL mode enabled, prepared statements for all queries, and proper JSON serialization for complex fields (dependencies, permissions). The `INSERT OR REPLACE` strategy handles re-registration cleanly.\n\n**Solid error handling in the sandbox runner.** The catch block in `/workspace/src/runner/index.ts` (lines 42-58) correctly handles the fact that VM errors may not be standard `Error` instances from the outer context, using duck-typing to extract `.message`.\n\n**Good test coverage.** The 85 tests cover the happy paths, error cases, edge cases (empty inputs, nonexistent entities, circular dependencies), and an end-to-end lifecycle test.\n\n**Correct semver delegation.** The resolver delegates directly to the `semver` library rather than reimplementing version comparison logic, which is the right approach.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Issues\n\n### IMPORTANT (Should Fix)\n\n**4.1. Registry `get()` uses lexicographic sort, not semver sort.**\n\nIn `/workspace/src/registry/index.ts`, line 27:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM plugins WHERE name = ? ORDER BY version DESC LIMIT 1\n```\n\nThis sorts versions as strings, not by semver precedence. For example, version `9.0.0` would sort above `10.0.0` lexicographically. The `get()` method is documented as returning the \"latest\" version, but `ORDER BY version DESC` performs a text comparison, not a semantic version comparison.\n\nThe test at line 115-122 of `/workspace/tests/registry.test.ts` deliberately avoids asserting which specific version is returned, noting only \"get() returns the latest by descending version string sort\" -- the test is aware of this limitation but does not enforce correctness.\n\n**Recommendation**: Either (a) fetch all versions, parse them with `semver.maxSatisfying(versions, '*')`, and return that, or (b) document clearly that `get()` returns an arbitrary version rather than the semantically latest one. Since the `DepsService` relies on `registry.get()` to build dependency trees, incorrect \"latest\" resolution could produce wrong dependency graphs.\n\n**4.2. Registry and ReviewService use separate database instances when both are given `:memory:`.**\n\nIn `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 32-36:\n```typescript\nexport function createMarketplace(dbPath?: string): Marketplace {\n  const registry = createRegistry(dbPath);\n  // ...\n  const reviews = createReviewService(dbPath);\n```\n\nWhen `dbPath` is `undefined` (the default), both services default to `:memory:`, which creates two independent in-memory databases. This is actually correct behavior for isolation, but if a user passes a file path expecting them to share a database, they would get table name collisions or separate connections. This is acceptable for the current requirements but worth noting for future extensibility.\n\n**4.3. `installPlugin` registers the plugin BEFORE checking for circular dependencies.**\n\nIn `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 52-71:\n```typescript\n// 2. Register the plugin\nregistry.register(manifest);\n\n// ... resolve deps ...\n\n// 4. Check for circular dependencies\nif (deps.hasCircularDependency(manifest.name, registry)) {\n  throw new Error(`Circular dependency detected for plugin ${manifest.name}`);\n}\n```\n\nIf a circular dependency is detected, the plugin has already been registered in the catalog. The thrown error leaves the registry in an inconsistent state -- the plugin exists but was rejected. This means a subsequent `registry.get('a')` would return the plugin even though installation was rejected.\n\n**Recommendation**: Either (a) remove the plugin from the registry in the error path (`registry.remove(manifest.name, manifest.version)` before throwing), or (b) move the registration to after the cycle check passes. The test at `/workspace/tests/marketplace.test.ts` line 63-79 verifies the error is thrown but does not check post-error registry state.\n\n**4.4. DepsService `detectCycles` has a subtle bug with the `visited` set preventing full graph exploration.**\n\nIn `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts`, lines 40-62:\n```typescript\nfunction dfs(current: string, path: string[], visited: Set<string>, recStack: Set<string>): void {\n  visited.add(current);\n  recStack.add(current);\n  path.push(current);\n\n  const manifest = registry.get(current);\n  if (manifest) {\n    for (const depName of Object.keys(manifest.dependencies)) {\n      if (recStack.has(depName)) {\n        // Found a cycle\n        ...\n      } else if (!visited.has(depName)) {\n        dfs(depName, path, visited, recStack);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  path.pop();\n  recStack.delete(current);\n}\n```\n\nThe `visited` set is shared across all DFS branches, which means that once a node is fully explored from one path, it will not be re-explored from another path. In standard cycle detection for directed graphs (e.g., Tarjan's algorithm), the `visited` set prevents re-visiting fully explored nodes. However, since this DFS starts from a single root node, it works correctly for detecting cycles reachable from that root. The issue would only manifest if `detectCycles` were called to explore a disconnected graph, which is not the case here. This is a minor correctness note rather than a bug.\n\n### SUGGESTIONS (Nice to Have)\n\n**4.5. No input validation for review ratings.**\n\nIn `/workspace/src/reviews/index.ts`, the SQLite schema has a `CHECK(rating >= 1 AND rating <= 5)` constraint (line 14), but the `addReview` method at line 60 does not validate the rating in application code before attempting the insert. If an invalid rating (e.g., 0 or 6) is provided, the caller gets a raw SQLite constraint violation error rather than a descriptive application-level error.\n\n**Recommendation**: Add a guard at the start of `addReview`:\n```typescript\nif (review.rating < 1 || review.rating > 5) {\n  throw new Error('Rating must be between 1 and 5');\n}\n```\n\n**4.6. The `get()` method in registry returns the \"latest\" version by sort order, but `DepsService.buildTree` always calls `registry.get(name)` to resolve dependencies.**\n\nThis means dependency tree building always uses whatever `get()` returns (the lexicographically highest version), rather than using version resolution logic. For a real marketplace, you would want the dependency graph to respect the version constraints declared in `dependencies`. Currently in `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts`, line 9:\n```typescript\nconst manifest = registry.get(name);\n```\n\nThis means `buildTree('root', registry)` resolves all transitive dependencies to their \"latest\" versions regardless of what version ranges are declared. The version resolver is only used during `installPlugin` for the direct dependencies. This is a design limitation rather than a bug, since the requirements do not specify that the tree must be version-aware.\n\n**4.7. No cleanup/close method for database connections.**\n\nNeither `createRegistry` nor `createReviewService` expose a method to close the underlying `better-sqlite3` database connection. For in-memory databases in tests, this is fine (garbage collection handles it). For file-backed databases in production, unclosed connections could cause WAL file accumulation.\n\n**4.8. The `resolver.test.ts` file uses `beforeEach` without importing it.**\n\nIn `/workspace/tests/resolver.test.ts`, line 1:\n```typescript\nimport { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest';\n```\n\nThe `beforeEach` at line 8 is used but not imported. This works because `vitest.config.ts` has `globals: true`, which makes `beforeEach` available globally. However, it is inconsistent with the other test files (e.g., `registry.test.ts` and `reviews.test.ts`) which explicitly import `beforeEach`. This is a style inconsistency, not a functional issue.\n\n**4.9. Runner memory measurement is approximate.**\n\nIn `/workspace/src/runner/index.ts`, lines 11-12 and 29-30:\n```typescript\nconst startMem = process.memoryUsage().heapUsed;\n// ...\nconst memoryUsed = Math.max(0, process.memoryUsage().heapUsed - startMem);\n```\n\nSince `process.memoryUsage().heapUsed` measures the entire Node.js process heap, the difference can be affected by GC activity, other concurrent operations, or V8 internal allocations unrelated to the sandboxed code. The `Math.max(0, ...)` guard is a reasonable mitigation (GC during execution could make the delta negative), and this is acknowledged as a best-effort measurement given the constraints of the `vm` module.\n\n**4.10. No test for `registry.update` preserving name/version immutability.**\n\nIn `/workspace/src/registry/index.ts`, line 111:\n```typescript\nconst merged = { ...current, ...updates, name, version };\n```\n\nThis correctly prevents `name` and `version` from being overridden via the `updates` parameter, since they are spread last. However, no test verifies that passing `{ name: 'new-name' }` or `{ version: '9.9.9' }` in updates is safely ignored. Consider adding a test to lock in this behavior.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Test Quality Assessment\n\nThe tests are well-organized and cover the key functional scenarios:\n\n- **Registry** (16 tests): CRUD operations, search by name/description, multi-version handling, dependency/permission serialization roundtrip.\n- **Resolver** (13 tests): Constraint resolution (caret, tilde, exact, wildcard), error cases, individual utility methods.\n- **Runner** (10 tests): Expression evaluation, console.log capture, error handling (runtime + syntax), context passing, isolation between runs, timeout enforcement.\n- **Reviews** (16 tests): Add/get/remove/flag lifecycle, average rating with flagged exclusion, user-specific queries, count queries, edge cases (empty results, nonexistent entities).\n- **Deps** (16 tests): Tree building (leaf, nested, unknown plugin, circular), cycle detection (direct, indirect, acyclic, isolated), topological sort (linear, leaf, diamond), flatten (transitive, leaf, shared/diamond).\n- **Marketplace Integration** (14 tests): Install workflow, dependency resolution during install, circular dependency rejection, validation of required fields, entry point execution, service exposure, end-to-end lifecycle.\n\n**Missing edge case tests** (not critical, but would improve coverage):\n- Concurrent installs of the same plugin\n- Unicode/special characters in plugin names and descriptions\n- Very large dependency graphs (performance regression)\n- `installPlugin` post-error registry state (related to issue 4.3)\n- `update` with name/version in the updates parameter (related to issue 4.10)\n\n---\n\n## 6. Summary of Findings\n\n| Severity | Count | Summary |\n|---|---|---|\n| Critical (must fix) | 0 | None |\n| Important (should fix) | 3 | Lexicographic version sort in `get()`, stale registration on cycle detection failure, separate DB instances silently |\n| Suggestions | 6 | Rating validation, version-unaware dep trees, no DB close, import inconsistency, approximate memory, missing immutability test |\n\n**Overall Assessment**: This is a solid implementation. The architecture is clean, all interfaces are correctly implemented, all tests pass, the build and lint are clean, and the code is maintainable. The most actionable issue is **4.3** (the plugin remaining registered after a circular dependency rejection), which could cause confusion in production use. Issue **4.1** (lexicographic version sorting) would be a real problem once version numbers exceed single digits. These are both straightforward fixes that would bring the implementation from good to excellent."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a7196dd (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 43432\ntool_uses: 30\nduration_ms: 134526</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"eb7a9eca-78b6-451b-aaba-f4cd85e91db6","uuid":"90c8d77e-b2f1-4332-97ca-8dc56e07e159","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the plugin marketplace implementation against these requirements:\n\n1. Plugin Registry - SQLite-backed catalog with register, get, getVersion, list, search, remove, listVersions, update\n2. Version Resolver - semver constraint resolution \n3. Sandboxed Runner - VM-based isolated code execution with timeout\n4. Review System - ratings, flagging, averages (excluding flagged)\n5. Dependency Graph - tree building, cycle detection, topological sort, flatten\n6. Integration layer - createMarketplace() with installPlugin() workflow that validates, registers, resolves deps, checks cycles, executes in sandbox\n\nFocus on: correctness, edge cases, code quality, conformance to src/types.ts interfaces. Check that all tests pass and the build/lint succeed.","agentId":"a7196dd","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\n\n# Plugin Marketplace -- Code Review Report\n\n## Executive Summary\n\n**Build**: PASSES  \n**Lint**: PASSES  \n**Tests**: 85/85 PASS across 6 test suites  \n\nThe implementation is well-structured, follows the required architecture, and conforms to all interfaces defined in `src/types.ts`. All five modules plus the integration layer are implemented. The code is clean, readable, and the test coverage is solid. Below is a detailed analysis with issues categorized by severity.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Plan Alignment Analysis\n\nAll six required components are implemented and accounted for:\n\n| Requirement | Status | Location |\n|---|---|---|\n| Plugin Registry (SQLite-backed) | Implemented | `/workspace/src/registry/index.ts` |\n| Version Resolver (semver) | Implemented | `/workspace/src/resolver/index.ts` |\n| Sandboxed Runner (vm) | Implemented | `/workspace/src/runner/index.ts` |\n| Review System | Implemented | `/workspace/src/reviews/index.ts` |\n| Dependency Graph | Implemented | `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts` |\n| Integration layer (createMarketplace + installPlugin) | Implemented | `/workspace/src/index.ts` |\n\nThe `installPlugin` workflow follows the exact prescribed sequence: validate -> register -> resolve deps -> check cycles -> execute in sandbox -> return result.\n\nThe constraint \"Modules should only share types, not import each other directly\" is respected. The only cross-module imports happen in `/workspace/src/index.ts` (the integration layer), which is the correct place for composition.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Interface Conformance\n\nAll service interfaces from `/workspace/src/types.ts` are implemented with matching signatures:\n\n- **RegistryService**: All 8 methods (`register`, `get`, `getVersion`, `list`, `search`, `remove`, `listVersions`, `update`) -- CONFORMS\n- **ResolverService**: All 4 methods (`resolve`, `satisfies`, `maxSatisfying`, `validRange`) -- CONFORMS\n- **RunnerService**: Both methods (`execute`, `executeWithTimeout`) -- CONFORMS\n- **ReviewService**: All 8 methods (`addReview`, `getReviews`, `getAverageRating`, `flagReview`, `getFlaggedReviews`, `removeReview`, `getReviewsByUser`, `getReviewCount`) -- CONFORMS\n- **DepsService**: All 5 methods (`buildTree`, `detectCycles`, `topologicalSort`, `flattenDependencies`, `hasCircularDependency`) -- CONFORMS\n\n---\n\n## 3. What Was Done Well\n\n**Clean module architecture.** Each service is a self-contained factory function with no cross-dependencies. The integration layer composes them properly.\n\n**Correct use of SQLite.** Both the registry and review service use `better-sqlite3` with WAL mode enabled, prepared statements for all queries, and proper JSON serialization for complex fields (dependencies, permissions). The `INSERT OR REPLACE` strategy handles re-registration cleanly.\n\n**Solid error handling in the sandbox runner.** The catch block in `/workspace/src/runner/index.ts` (lines 42-58) correctly handles the fact that VM errors may not be standard `Error` instances from the outer context, using duck-typing to extract `.message`.\n\n**Good test coverage.** The 85 tests cover the happy paths, error cases, edge cases (empty inputs, nonexistent entities, circular dependencies), and an end-to-end lifecycle test.\n\n**Correct semver delegation.** The resolver delegates directly to the `semver` library rather than reimplementing version comparison logic, which is the right approach.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Issues\n\n### IMPORTANT (Should Fix)\n\n**4.1. Registry `get()` uses lexicographic sort, not semver sort.**\n\nIn `/workspace/src/registry/index.ts`, line 27:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM plugins WHERE name = ? ORDER BY version DESC LIMIT 1\n```\n\nThis sorts versions as strings, not by semver precedence. For example, version `9.0.0` would sort above `10.0.0` lexicographically. The `get()` method is documented as returning the \"latest\" version, but `ORDER BY version DESC` performs a text comparison, not a semantic version comparison.\n\nThe test at line 115-122 of `/workspace/tests/registry.test.ts` deliberately avoids asserting which specific version is returned, noting only \"get() returns the latest by descending version string sort\" -- the test is aware of this limitation but does not enforce correctness.\n\n**Recommendation**: Either (a) fetch all versions, parse them with `semver.maxSatisfying(versions, '*')`, and return that, or (b) document clearly that `get()` returns an arbitrary version rather than the semantically latest one. Since the `DepsService` relies on `registry.get()` to build dependency trees, incorrect \"latest\" resolution could produce wrong dependency graphs.\n\n**4.2. Registry and ReviewService use separate database instances when both are given `:memory:`.**\n\nIn `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 32-36:\n```typescript\nexport function createMarketplace(dbPath?: string): Marketplace {\n  const registry = createRegistry(dbPath);\n  // ...\n  const reviews = createReviewService(dbPath);\n```\n\nWhen `dbPath` is `undefined` (the default), both services default to `:memory:`, which creates two independent in-memory databases. This is actually correct behavior for isolation, but if a user passes a file path expecting them to share a database, they would get table name collisions or separate connections. This is acceptable for the current requirements but worth noting for future extensibility.\n\n**4.3. `installPlugin` registers the plugin BEFORE checking for circular dependencies.**\n\nIn `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 52-71:\n```typescript\n// 2. Register the plugin\nregistry.register(manifest);\n\n// ... resolve deps ...\n\n// 4. Check for circular dependencies\nif (deps.hasCircularDependency(manifest.name, registry)) {\n  throw new Error(`Circular dependency detected for plugin ${manifest.name}`);\n}\n```\n\nIf a circular dependency is detected, the plugin has already been registered in the catalog. The thrown error leaves the registry in an inconsistent state -- the plugin exists but was rejected. This means a subsequent `registry.get('a')` would return the plugin even though installation was rejected.\n\n**Recommendation**: Either (a) remove the plugin from the registry in the error path (`registry.remove(manifest.name, manifest.version)` before throwing), or (b) move the registration to after the cycle check passes. The test at `/workspace/tests/marketplace.test.ts` line 63-79 verifies the error is thrown but does not check post-error registry state.\n\n**4.4. DepsService `detectCycles` has a subtle bug with the `visited` set preventing full graph exploration.**\n\nIn `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts`, lines 40-62:\n```typescript\nfunction dfs(current: string, path: string[], visited: Set<string>, recStack: Set<string>): void {\n  visited.add(current);\n  recStack.add(current);\n  path.push(current);\n\n  const manifest = registry.get(current);\n  if (manifest) {\n    for (const depName of Object.keys(manifest.dependencies)) {\n      if (recStack.has(depName)) {\n        // Found a cycle\n        ...\n      } else if (!visited.has(depName)) {\n        dfs(depName, path, visited, recStack);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  path.pop();\n  recStack.delete(current);\n}\n```\n\nThe `visited` set is shared across all DFS branches, which means that once a node is fully explored from one path, it will not be re-explored from another path. In standard cycle detection for directed graphs (e.g., Tarjan's algorithm), the `visited` set prevents re-visiting fully explored nodes. However, since this DFS starts from a single root node, it works correctly for detecting cycles reachable from that root. The issue would only manifest if `detectCycles` were called to explore a disconnected graph, which is not the case here. This is a minor correctness note rather than a bug.\n\n### SUGGESTIONS (Nice to Have)\n\n**4.5. No input validation for review ratings.**\n\nIn `/workspace/src/reviews/index.ts`, the SQLite schema has a `CHECK(rating >= 1 AND rating <= 5)` constraint (line 14), but the `addReview` method at line 60 does not validate the rating in application code before attempting the insert. If an invalid rating (e.g., 0 or 6) is provided, the caller gets a raw SQLite constraint violation error rather than a descriptive application-level error.\n\n**Recommendation**: Add a guard at the start of `addReview`:\n```typescript\nif (review.rating < 1 || review.rating > 5) {\n  throw new Error('Rating must be between 1 and 5');\n}\n```\n\n**4.6. The `get()` method in registry returns the \"latest\" version by sort order, but `DepsService.buildTree` always calls `registry.get(name)` to resolve dependencies.**\n\nThis means dependency tree building always uses whatever `get()` returns (the lexicographically highest version), rather than using version resolution logic. For a real marketplace, you would want the dependency graph to respect the version constraints declared in `dependencies`. Currently in `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts`, line 9:\n```typescript\nconst manifest = registry.get(name);\n```\n\nThis means `buildTree('root', registry)` resolves all transitive dependencies to their \"latest\" versions regardless of what version ranges are declared. The version resolver is only used during `installPlugin` for the direct dependencies. This is a design limitation rather than a bug, since the requirements do not specify that the tree must be version-aware.\n\n**4.7. No cleanup/close method for database connections.**\n\nNeither `createRegistry` nor `createReviewService` expose a method to close the underlying `better-sqlite3` database connection. For in-memory databases in tests, this is fine (garbage collection handles it). For file-backed databases in production, unclosed connections could cause WAL file accumulation.\n\n**4.8. The `resolver.test.ts` file uses `beforeEach` without importing it.**\n\nIn `/workspace/tests/resolver.test.ts`, line 1:\n```typescript\nimport { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest';\n```\n\nThe `beforeEach` at line 8 is used but not imported. This works because `vitest.config.ts` has `globals: true`, which makes `beforeEach` available globally. However, it is inconsistent with the other test files (e.g., `registry.test.ts` and `reviews.test.ts`) which explicitly import `beforeEach`. This is a style inconsistency, not a functional issue.\n\n**4.9. Runner memory measurement is approximate.**\n\nIn `/workspace/src/runner/index.ts`, lines 11-12 and 29-30:\n```typescript\nconst startMem = process.memoryUsage().heapUsed;\n// ...\nconst memoryUsed = Math.max(0, process.memoryUsage().heapUsed - startMem);\n```\n\nSince `process.memoryUsage().heapUsed` measures the entire Node.js process heap, the difference can be affected by GC activity, other concurrent operations, or V8 internal allocations unrelated to the sandboxed code. The `Math.max(0, ...)` guard is a reasonable mitigation (GC during execution could make the delta negative), and this is acknowledged as a best-effort measurement given the constraints of the `vm` module.\n\n**4.10. No test for `registry.update` preserving name/version immutability.**\n\nIn `/workspace/src/registry/index.ts`, line 111:\n```typescript\nconst merged = { ...current, ...updates, name, version };\n```\n\nThis correctly prevents `name` and `version` from being overridden via the `updates` parameter, since they are spread last. However, no test verifies that passing `{ name: 'new-name' }` or `{ version: '9.9.9' }` in updates is safely ignored. Consider adding a test to lock in this behavior.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Test Quality Assessment\n\nThe tests are well-organized and cover the key functional scenarios:\n\n- **Registry** (16 tests): CRUD operations, search by name/description, multi-version handling, dependency/permission serialization roundtrip.\n- **Resolver** (13 tests): Constraint resolution (caret, tilde, exact, wildcard), error cases, individual utility methods.\n- **Runner** (10 tests): Expression evaluation, console.log capture, error handling (runtime + syntax), context passing, isolation between runs, timeout enforcement.\n- **Reviews** (16 tests): Add/get/remove/flag lifecycle, average rating with flagged exclusion, user-specific queries, count queries, edge cases (empty results, nonexistent entities).\n- **Deps** (16 tests): Tree building (leaf, nested, unknown plugin, circular), cycle detection (direct, indirect, acyclic, isolated), topological sort (linear, leaf, diamond), flatten (transitive, leaf, shared/diamond).\n- **Marketplace Integration** (14 tests): Install workflow, dependency resolution during install, circular dependency rejection, validation of required fields, entry point execution, service exposure, end-to-end lifecycle.\n\n**Missing edge case tests** (not critical, but would improve coverage):\n- Concurrent installs of the same plugin\n- Unicode/special characters in plugin names and descriptions\n- Very large dependency graphs (performance regression)\n- `installPlugin` post-error registry state (related to issue 4.3)\n- `update` with name/version in the updates parameter (related to issue 4.10)\n\n---\n\n## 6. Summary of Findings\n\n| Severity | Count | Summary |\n|---|---|---|\n| Critical (must fix) | 0 | None |\n| Important (should fix) | 3 | Lexicographic version sort in `get()`, stale registration on cycle detection failure, separate DB instances silently |\n| Suggestions | 6 | Rating validation, version-unaware dep trees, no DB close, import inconsistency, approximate memory, missing immutability test |\n\n**Overall Assessment**: This is a solid implementation. The architecture is clean, all interfaces are correctly implemented, all tests pass, the build and lint are clean, and the code is maintainable. The most actionable issue is **4.3** (the plugin remaining registered after a circular dependency rejection), which could cause confusion in production use. Issue **4.1** (lexicographic version sorting) would be a real problem once version numbers exceed single digits. These are both straightforward fixes that would bring the implementation from good to excellent."}],"totalDurationMs":134526,"totalTokens":43432,"totalToolUseCount":30,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":392,"cache_read_input_tokens":39546,"output_tokens":3493,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":392,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[]}}}
